nal\n\n  Line 24:   - which tool\n\n  Line 27:   - memory_search\n\n  Line 28:   - memory_context\n\n  Line 33: > Lean constitutional rule. Always-surface guidance for picking the right retrieval tool by query shape.\n\n  Line 49: | **Spec-doc continuity** (prior work, decisions) | `memory_search` / `memory_context` | `memory_match_triggers` |\n\n  Line 50: | **Broad topic** (thematic overview) | `memory_search` with `retrievalLevel: \"global\"` | community search fallback |\n\n  Line 54: When both graph and semantic search miss or return weak results, apply the 3-tier FTS fallback:\n\n  Line 83: | `code_graph_query` | `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tools/code-graph-tools.ts` | Structural query handler (callers/imports/deps) |\n\n  Line 84: | `code_graph_context` | `.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tools/code-graph-tools.ts` | Bounded code-graph context retrieval |\n\n  Line 85: | `memory_search` | `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-search.ts` | 3-channel hybrid search with RRF fusion |\n\n  Line 86: | `memory_context` | `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-context.ts` | Intent-routed context retrieval (L1 entry point) |\n\n  Line 87: | `memory_match_triggers` | `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/handlers/memory-triggers.ts` | Trigger-phrase matcher (constitutional + tier-aware) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/README.md:\n  Line 5:   - \"constitutional memory\"\n\n  Line 7:   - \"constitutional tier\"\n\n  Line 18: `constitutional/` contains Markdown rule files indexed as the constitutional tier in Spec Kit Memory. Constitutional records are intended for global rules that must surface before ordinary search results, such as gate enforcement and search-tool routing.\n\n  Line 22: - The folder contains 12 active rule files spanning gate enforcement, tool routing, CLI dispatch, comment hygiene, memory-system and DB-topology rules, completion verification, deep-review, and naming conventions (see §2 Package Topology). It originated with just `gate-enforcement.md` and `gate-tool-routing.md`.\n\n  Line 23: - Rule files use frontmatter with `importanceTier: constitutional` and trigger phrases.\n\n  Line 26: - Constitutional rules support agent safety and retrieval routing. They do not replace packet recovery from `handover.md`, `_memory.continuity` and canonical spec docs.\n\n  Line 33: constitutional/\n\n  Line 39: +-- gate-tool-routing.md                          # Search and retrieval routing decision tree\n\n  Line 41: +-- memory-db-file-topology.md                    # Index DB and vector stores are separate files; treat as one unit\n\n  Line 42: +-- memory-system-spec-kit-only.md                # Use Spec Kit Memory only; never write Claude native memory unprompted\n\n  Line 45: +-- verify-before-completion-claims.md            # Gate completion claims on a positive check you actually read\n\n  Line 54: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 71: constitutional/*.md -> memory indexing metadata\n\n  Line 72: memory_search() -> constitutional records first, then query results\n\n  Line 73: memory_match_triggers() -> trigger phrase matches\n\n  Line 79: constitutional rules -> packet-specific status or mutable packet history\n\n  Line 80: constitutional rules -> runtime code behavior not enforced elsewhere\n\n  Line 89: constitutional/\n\n  Line 95: +-- gate-tool-routing.md                          # Search and retrieval routing decision tree\n\n  Line 97: +-- memory-db-file-topology.md                    # Index DB and vector stores are separate files; treat as one unit\n\n  Line 98: +-- memory-system-spec-kit-only.md                # Use Spec Kit Memory only; never write Claude native memory unprompted\n\n  Line 101: +-- verify-before-completion-claims.md            # Gate completion claims on a positive check you actually read\n\n  Line 118: | `gate-tool-routing.md` | Search and retrieval routing across memory, code graph, and the FTS fallback chain. |\n\n  Line 119: | `main-branch-direct-push.md` | Owner's AIs push directly to `main`; the protected-branch bypass is expected and authorized. |\n\n  Line 120: | `memory-db-file-topology.md` | The index DB and embedding vectors live in separate files; wipe/restore/integrity-check them as one unit. |\n\n  Line 121: | `memory-system-spec-kit-only.md` | Use Spec Kit Memory for all saves; never write Claude native memory unless explicitly asked. |\n\n  Line 123: | `spec-folder-naming.md` | `NNN-short-name` convention and the rename/move procedure (`git mv`, never delete + recreate). |\n\n  Line 124: | `verify-before-completion-claims.md` | Gate every completion claim on a positive check whose result you actually read. |\n\n  Line 133: | Imports | Rule files are Markdown inputs for memory indexing. They do not import code. |\n\n  Line 134: | Exports | Indexed records surface through memory search and trigger matching. |\n\n  Line 137: | Visibility budget | Keep each constitutional rule lean enough for the `maxTokens: 2000` budget in `importance-tiers.ts`. |\n\n  Line 144: │ constitutional/*.md                      │\n\n  Line 154: │ memory_save or memory_index_scan         │\n\n  Line 159: │ constitutional-tier memory records       │\n\n  Line 174: | `*.md` rule files (12) | Rule document | Always-surfaced constitutional guidance; see §4 Key Files for the full list. |\n\n  Line 175: | `memory_search({ includeConstitutional: true })` | MCP tool behavior | Returns constitutional records before query-relevant records by default. |\n\n  Line 176: | `memory_match_triggers({ prompt })` | MCP tool behavior | Surfaces matching rules from trigger phrases. |\n\n  Line 177: | `memory_save({ filePath })` | MCP tool behavior | Indexes a single constitutional rule file. |\n\n  Line 178: | `memory_index_scan({ includeConstitutional: true })` | MCP tool behavior | Scans constitutional rule files with other indexed docs. |\n\n  Line 187: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/README.md\n\n  Line 193: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/extract_structure.py .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/README.md\n\n  Line 196: Expected result: structure extraction reports no critical README issues.\n\n  Line 201: memory_save({ filePath: \".opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/gate-enforcement.md\", force: true })\n\n  Line 211: - [`./gate-tool-routing.md`](./gate-tool-routing.md)\n\n  Line 213: - [`../mcp_server/lib/scoring/importance-tiers.ts`](../mcp_server/lib/scoring/importance-tiers.ts)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/memory-db-file-topology.md:\n  Line 3: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 6:   - where is the memory database\n\n  Line 10:   - wipe the memory db\n\n  Line 11:   - reindex the memory db\n\n  Line 12:   - restore the memory db\n\n  Line 14:   - quick_check memory\n\n  Line 26: The memory data lives under `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/database/`, split across distinct files. **Embeddings are NOT inside `context-index.sqlite`** — they are in separate per-embedding-profile files under `database/vectors/`. Any operation that wipes, restores, backs up, or integrity-checks the memory store **must treat the index DB and the active vector store together**, or the index and vectors silently diverge.\n\n  Line 31:   Holds lexical + FTS (`memory_index`, `memory_fts*`), the **causal graph** (`causal_edges`, `memory_entities`, `entity_catalog`, `memory_summaries`, `graph_communities`), `checkpoints`, `config`, `vec_metadata` (vector *metadata/linkage*, not the vectors), and scoring/working tables. Schema version in `schema_version` (currently v30, `journal_mode=wal`).\n\n  Line 36: - **Runtime state (in `database/`)** — `.mk-spec-memory-launcher.json` (the shared-daemon **lease**: `{pid, ownerPid, childPid}`), `.unclean-shutdown` and `.needs-rebuild` (boot self-heal **sentinels**).\n\n  Line 37: - **IPC socket (NOT under `database/`)** — `/tmp/mk-spec-memory/daemon-ipc.sock`, dir pinned by `SPECKIT_IPC_SOCKET_DIR=/tmp/mk-spec-memory`. New sessions bridge to the owner daemon over this socket.\n\n  Line 42: On 2026-06-04 an operator assumed embeddings lived inside `context-index.sqlite`. A `quick_check`/wipe/recovery that touched only `context-index.sqlite` would have left the `database/vectors/` store unmanaged, diverging index rows from their vectors. Real corruption hit `memory_index` (from a concurrent **second** direct SQLite connection writing while the daemon was live — a single-writer violation), and recovery required reasoning about both files. Knowing the split up front prevents half-recoveries, false \"DB is clean\" conclusions, and orphaned vectors. (Owner directive, 2026-06-04.)\n\n  Line 46: 1. **Wipe / restore / backup** → act on **both** `context-index.sqlite` (+ wal/shm) **and** `database/vectors/<active-profile>.sqlite` (+ wal/shm) as a unit. A full from-source reindex discards the causal graph (it lives in `context-index.sqlite`), so plan to re-enrich after.\n\n  Line 47: 2. **Integrity** → run `PRAGMA quick_check` on **each** file; reconcile `memory_index` count vs `memory_fts` count vs vector rows. `quick_check ok` on the index alone does **not** certify embeddings.\n\n  Line 50: 5. **Connectivity check (read-only)** → a JSON-RPC `initialize` to `/tmp/mk-spec-memory/daemon-ipc.sock` returning in <100ms with `serverInfo.name=mk-spec-memory` means new sessions will connect; no process action needed.\n\n  Line 55: - Routine `memory_save` / search through the daemon (it manages the index↔vector linkage internally).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/verify-before-completion-claims.md:\n  Line 3: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 13:   - claim completion\n\n  Line 21: Never claim an outcome (\"done\", \"committed\", \"validate passed\", \"green\", \"it works\") from the **absence** of an error. Gate every completion on a positive check whose result you actually read.\n\n  Line 25: Across long sessions, status was repeatedly stated BEFORE it was true — a commit silently blocked by the comment-hygiene pre-commit gate, a strict-validate that was actually FAILED, a doc Edit that silently failed (\"string not found\") yet was credited in the commit message, a Step-0 boot marked PASS when the daemon had exited with EINVAL, and a fabricated commit hash written into a memory for a commit that never landed. Each was caught only by a later re-check. A false \"done\" is worse than a slow \"done\" because downstream steps build on a state that isn't real. (Owner: \"Report outcomes faithfully\"; \"never claim an unverified commit/file.\")\n\n  Line 31: - **Edit** → confirm the new text is on disk; the Edit tool errors if `old_string` didn't match — treat that error as \"the change did NOT happen.\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/spec-folder-naming.md:\n  Line 3: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 20: Spec folders use `NNN-short-descriptive-name`. Canonical source: `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/structure/folder_structure.md` §2.\n\n  Line 26: - Describe the work/outcome literally, NOT the method or tooling.\n\n  Line 33: 1. `git mv` the folder (preserves `git log --follow`). NEVER delete + recreate.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/main-branch-direct-push.md:\n  Line 3: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 24: The `main` branch (`MichelKerkmeester/opencode--spec-kit-skilled-agent-orchestration`) has GitHub protection (PR required, verified signatures, code scanning). The owner's account bypasses these — a direct push succeeds with a \"Bypassed rule violations\" notice; the commit is unsigned and flagged. The owner clarified (2026-05-27) that **these rules gate external contributors, and any AI working under the owner's command is authorized to bypass them.** Treating the bypass as a blocker is unwanted friction. This overrides sk-git's generic \"never commit to protected branches\" rule for this repo + owner.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/code-graph-scope-intent.md:\n  Line 3: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 20: In THIS repo the code-graph (`mk-code-index`) indexes the entire `.opencode` tooling tree, not just app code. Treat the \"index everything\" active scope as intentional, never as a misconfiguration to \"fix.\"\n\n  Line 24: - **Default (for repo cloners / end users):** index only their own app code (e.g. `/src`). The `.opencode` tooling tree (skills, agents, commands, specs, plugins) is **opt-in and OFF by default** — `code_graph_scan` defaults `includeSkills`/`includeAgents`/`includeCommands`/`includeSpecs`/`includePlugins` to `false`.\n\n  Line 25: - **This repo (owner setup):** overrides the default via env (`SPECKIT_CODE_GRAPH_INDEX_*=true`) so the graph also covers `.opencode` skill/tooling code, because skill/tooling development happens here. That is why `code_graph_status` shows active scope `skills=all:agents=all:commands=all:specs=all:plugins=all`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/constitutional/bash-output-truncation-verdict-visibility.md:\n  Line 3: importanceTier: constitutional\n\n  Line 11:   - tool-results file\n\n  Line 20: Never infer a command's result from blank, truncated, or absent Bash output. When a Bash command's combined output exceeds ~2KB, the harness returns only a **preview (first ~2KB)** and writes the full output to a `tool-results/<id>.txt` file. Some calls also return apparently-empty output while the real result lands in the **preview of a *later* tool call** (display lag). Treat blank/lagged output as UNKNOWN, not success.\n\n\n(Results truncated: showing 100 of 136 matches (36 hidden). Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":136,"truncated":true},"title":"constitutional|protected|memory|manual|overwrite|feedback|source|forge|immunity|tier|critical|delete|completion|tool","time":{"start":1780738202930,"end":1780738202963}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_074fc42c9c285a90016a23e89ab4588191893ad5340a3b3eae"}},"id":"prt_e9c449d12001MxqpwX2NWTv5GN","sessionID":"ses_163bcc508ffey1OIiwa9Lcz6qq","messageID":"msg_e9c4464c80019P1neaW2idvv1d"}}
